Exercise 1:

double.factorial<- function(n){ #declare function
  doublefact=1;#set variable to initial value
  for(i in 1:n){ #begin loop up to number
    if(i%%2!=0){   #if number is odd, then multiply by number
      doublefact=doublefact*i;
    }
  }
  return (doublefact) #return value
}
double.factorial(7)

my.std<-function(dataset){#declare function
  standardDev=0; # set result to 0
  n=length(dataset); # get length of data set
  mean=0; #set variable to 0
  for(j in 1:n){ # loop through data to get sum
    mean=mean +dataset[j];
  }
  mean=mean/n; #divide sum to get the mean
  x=sum((dataset-mean)^2) #find the sum of the squares
  var=x/(n-1) # find the variance
  standardDev=sqrt(var) #sqrt to find the sd
  return(standardDev); # return result
}

Exercise 4:

A 99% confidence interval would be wider than the 90% interval because it is more likely to include the true mean since it only has a 1% chance of being wrong and the margin of error is greater. A point estimate would be 150/400, which is 37.5%

#90%
n=400
phat=150/n
phat 
## [1] 0.375
z.value=qnorm((1-0.9)/2)
ME=z.value*sqrt(phat*(1-phat)/n)
ME
## [1] -0.03981557
CI=phat+c(ME,-ME)
CI
## [1] 0.3351844 0.4148156
#95%
z.value2=qnorm((1-0.99)/2)
ME2=z.value2*sqrt(phat*(1-phat)/n)
ME2
## [1] -0.0623509
CI2=phat+c(ME2,-ME2)
CI2
## [1] 0.3126491 0.4373509

glm.probs=predict(glm.fits,test1,type="response")
dim(test1)
## [1] 2000    4
glm.pred=rep("No",2000)
glm.pred[glm.probs>.5]="Yes"
